class ShapesPainter extends CustomPainter {
  @override
  void paint(Canvas canvas, Size size) {
    drawRectangle(canvas, size);
    drawCircle(canvas, size);
  }

  void drawRectangle(Canvas canvas, Size size) {
    final rect = Rect.fromLTWH(size.width / 4, size.height / 4, size.width / 2, size.height / 2);
    final paint = Paint()..color = Colors.green;

    canvas.drawRect(rect, paint);
  }

  void drawCircle(Canvas canvas, Size size) {
    final center = Offset(size.width / 2, size.height / 2);
    final radius = size.width / 4;
    final paint = Paint()..color = Colors.orange;

    canvas.drawCircle(center, radius, paint);
  }

  @override
  bool shouldRepaint(covariant CustomPainter oldDelegate) {
    return false;
  }
}

Animations in Flutter are essential for building engaging user interfaces.
However, they can impact performance. Let's look at some best practices to
optimize them and provide a seamless user experience.


PERFORMANCE CONSIDERATION

Flutter renders animations at the rasterization stage. If the location or
appearance changes, the entire frame undergoes re-rasterization. Multiple
simultaneous animations can compound this effect, leading to a potential
performance bottleneck.


ANIMATION TECHNIQUES

 1. Frame Skipping: For subtler animations, you can skip frames, reducing the
    rendering load. However, this can make animations appear less smooth.

 2. Throttling: Adjust the speed of the animation based on context. For
    instance, if the user is rapidly swiping a carousel, you might want to slow
    down the animation. Dart's Schedule library offers mechanisms for this.

 3. Micro-Animations: Limited to a specific area or element, these don't affect
    the entire frame, leading to better performance. Using smaller SizedBox
    objects, for example, can achieve the desired visual effect without
    redrawing the complete screen.

 4. Physics-Based Animations: Use these to mimic natural phenomena, enhancing
    user experience while minimizing performance impact.


CODE EXAMPLE: SKIPPING FRAMES

Here is the Dart code:

final controller = AnimationController(
  duration: const Duration(seconds: 2),
  vsync: this,
);

controller.addListener(() {
  if (controller.value % 0.1 != 0) { // Skip frames for smoothness
    return;
  }
  // Update UI
});



CODE EXAMPLE: THROTTLING

Here is the Dart code:

final accelerometerEvents = AcceleroMeterEvents();
double _lastTime = 0.0;

accelerometerEvents.listen((AccelerometerEvent event) {
  final time = DateTime.now().millisecondsSinceEpoch;
  if (time - _lastTime < 1000) { // Throttle for 1 second
    return;
  }
  _lastTime = time;

  // Process event further
});

