In Flutter, you can implement a swipe-to-dismiss feature for widgets, such as
list items, using the Dismissible widget.


DISMISSIBLE WIDGET

The Dismissible widget is based on the ListTile widget and is primarily used in
lists. Once the user swipes the widget in the specified direction (default is
horizontal), the widget is removed from the list and triggers a callback.

KEY PARAMETERS

 * key: It is crucial to provide a unique key for each Dismissible widget in a
   list.
 * onDismissed: A function that is executed when the user dismisses the widget.
   You can use this to remove the item from your list, database, or any other
   required operation.
 * background: A widget displayed behind the main one when it is swiped.
 * secondaryBackground: Optional, a widget displayed behind background when
   swiping in the opposite direction.

CODE EXAMPLE

Here is the Flutter code:

List<String> items = ['Item 1', 'Item 2', 'Item 3'];

class DismissibleExample extends StatefulWidget {
  @override
  _DismissibleExampleState createState() => _DismissibleExampleState();
}

class _DismissibleExampleState extends State<DismissibleExample> {
  @override
  Widget build(BuildContext context) {
    return Scaffold(
      appBar: AppBar(
        title: Text('Dismissible Example'),
      ),
      body: ListView.builder(
        itemCount: items.length,
        itemBuilder: (context, index) {
          final item = items[index];
          return Dismissible(
            key: Key(item),
            onDismissed: (direction) {
              setState(() {
                items.removeAt(index);
              });
              ScaffoldMessenger.of(context).showSnackBar(SnackBar(content: Text('$item dismissed')));
            },
            background: Container(
              color: Colors.red,
              child: Icon(Icons.delete, color: Colors.white, size: 36),
              alignment: Alignment.centerLeft,
              padding: EdgeInsets.only(left: 20.0),
            ),
            child: ListTile(
              title: Text('$item'),
            ),
          );
        },
      ),
    );
  }
}



IMPLEMENTING CALLBACKS

In the example, the onDismissed callback is used to remove the item from the
list and show a dismiss confirmation snackbar. It's essential to call setState
when updating the state of the widget after the item is dismissed.

Additionally, when swiping in a specific direction (endToStartDirection and
startToEndDirection), the background widget is shown. If you want to provide
different backgrounds for different swipe directions, you can use
secondaryBackground.

Routing in Flutter refers to the mechanism of navigating between different
sections or pages of your app. Flutter apps use a single activity and multiple
fragments (screens) pattern and streamline this process using Navigator.

Flutter employs a concept called delegation, passing control and information
from one Route to another.


KEY NAVIGATOR RESPONSIBILITIES

ROUTE MANAGEMENT

 * Push: Adds a new route to the stack, taking the user to that location.
 * Pop: Removes the top-most route from the stack, navigating the user to the
   previous location.

VISUAL REPRESENTATION

 * Transition: Manages animated transitions when routes are pushed or popped.

STACK CONTROL

 * Replacement: Swaps a route on the stack with another.


TYPES OF ROUTES

 1. Modal: Requires user action before returning to the previous route. Common
    examples are dialogs and bottom sheets.

 2. Non-Modal: Users can freely navigate to other routes without needing to
    address these first.


ROUTE JUSTIFICATION

 * Screen-Oriented: Best-suited for apps with distinct, full-screen feature
   sets.
 * Section-Oriented: Ideal for apps that emphasize continuous user journeys,
   like in a news reader where users explore from one article to another.


CODE EXAMPLE: NAVIGATOR

Here is the Flutter Dart code:

class HomeScreen extends StatelessWidget {
  @override
  Widget build(BuildContext context) {
    return Scaffold(
      appBar: AppBar(title: Text('Home')),
      body: Center(
        child: ElevatedButton(
          onPressed: () {
            Navigator.push(
              context,
              MaterialPageRoute(builder: (context) => DetailScreen()),
            );
          },
          child: Text('Go to Detail'),
        ),
      ),
    );
  }
}

class DetailScreen extends StatelessWidget {
  @override
  Widget build(BuildContext context) {
    return Scaffold(
      appBar: AppBar(title: Text('Detail')),
      body: Center(
        child: ElevatedButton(
          onPressed: () {
            Navigator.pop(context);
          },
          child: Text('Back to Home'),
        ),
      ),
    );
  }
}

In Flutter, you can pass data from one screen to another using multiple methods
such as constructor arguments, members, and global singletons. Let's review each
method.


BASIC METHODS

USING CONSTRUCTOR ARGUMENTS

One of the easiest ways to send data between screens is to include the necessary
data as arguments in the constructor of the target screen.

Here is the ReceivingScreen:

class ReceivingScreen extends StatelessWidget {
  final String message;

  ReceivingScreen({this.message});

  @override
  Widget build(BuildContext context) {
    return Center(
      child: Text(message),
    );
  }
}


and the SendingScreen which navigates to ReceivingScreen and passes the data:

class SendingScreen extends StatelessWidget {
  @override
  Widget build(BuildContext context) {
    return ElevatedButton(
      onPressed: () {
        Navigator.push(
          context,
          MaterialPageRoute(builder: (context) => ReceivingScreen(message: 'Hello!')),
        );
      },
      child: Text('Send Message'),
    );
  }
}


USING NAMED ROUTES

Another technique when navigating with named routes is to define a route setting
that provides the necessary data using arguments.

In main.dart:

void main() {
  runApp(MyApp());
}

class MyApp extends StatelessWidget {
  @override
  Widget build(BuildContext context) {
    return MaterialApp(
      routes: {
        '/': (context) => SendingScreen(),
        '/second': (context) => ReceivingScreen(),
      },
    );
  }
}


Your SendingScreen can then call the receiving screen with the named route:

class SendingScreen extends StatelessWidget {
  @override
  Widget build(BuildContext context) {
    return ElevatedButton(
      onPressed: () {
        Navigator.pushNamed(
          context,
          '/second',
          arguments: 'Hello!',
        );
      },
      child: Text('Send Message'),
    );
  }
}


In your ReceivingScreen, you can use ModalRoute.of to access the passed
arguments:

class ReceivingScreen extends StatelessWidget {
  @override
  Widget build(BuildContext context) {
    final String message = ModalRoute.of(context).settings.arguments;
    return Center(
      child: Text(message),
    );
  }
}


For complex apps or specific needs, you might consider using more advanced
tools, such as provider patterns, Riverpod, inherited widgets, or even state
