Deep linking enables directing users to specific content within a mobile app,
even if the app isn't currently open.

In the context of Flutter, deep linking ensures that both iOS and Android
platforms can handle external URLs and route users to the relevant parts of the
app.


KEY COMPONENTS

 * URI Scheme: A unique identifier, like myapp://, that signals the start of a
   deep link.

 * Path: The specific route within the app, often resembling a web URL, for
   example, myapp://profile.

 * Query Parameters: Additional data for context, like the user ID in
   myapp://profile?userID=123.


BRIDGING PLATFORMS

To manage deep linking across both iOS and Android platforms, Flutter developers
can integrate a unified approach using url_launcher and firebase_dynamic_links.


COMMON PATTERNS

 * Basic Link: Brings users to a default screen, commonly serving as a home
   screen.

   * Example: myapp://

 * Path-based Link: Navigates users to a specific in-app location.

   * Example: myapp://settings

 * Link with Parameters: Delivers users to a particular location tailored to the
   provided parameters.

   * Example: myapp://profile?userID=123


THE WORKFLOW

 1. Link Generation: Creating a deep link, often involving the assembly of the
    base URI, the path, and any necessary parameters.
 2. Link Sharing: Disseminating the deep link, commonly through mediums like
    SMS, email, or social media.
 3. App Handling: The app, upon being opened via a deep link, must interpret and
    act upon the deep link.
 4. Navigation: Based on the deep link, direct the user to the appropriate
    in-app location.


FEATURES AND LIMITATIONS

 * User Profiling: Allows streamlined user experiences, although this calls for
   proper handling of privacy considerations.

 * Analytical Insights: Ensures attribution and aids in understanding how users
   engage with the app.

 * Restrictions on App Stores: Apple's App Store policy necessitates clear user
   consent for accessing sensitive data shared via deep links.


CODE EXAMPLE: DEEP LINKING

Here is the Flutter code:

import 'package:flutter/material.dart';
import 'package:url_launcher/url_launcher.dart';
import 'package:firebase_dynamic_links/firebase_dynamic_links.dart';

void main() => runApp(MyApp());

class MyApp extends StatelessWidget {

  @override
  Widget build(BuildContext context) {
    return MaterialApp(
      onGenerateRoute: (settings) {
        if (settings.name == '/profile') {
          var userID = settings.arguments as String;
          return MaterialPageRoute(builder: (context) => Profile(userID: userID));
        }
      },
      home: MyHomePage(),
    );
  }

  // Generate basic deep link
  String generateDeepLink() {
    return 'myapp://';
  }

  // Generate deep link for profile with user ID
  String generateUserProfileLink(String userID) {
    return 'myapp://profile?userID=$userID';
  }

  @override
  void initState() {
    super.initState();
    handleDynamicLinks();
  }

  Future<void> handleDynamicLinks() async {
    final PendingDynamicLinkData? data = await FirebaseDynamicLinks.instance.getInitialLink();
    final Uri? deepLink = data?.link;

    if (deepLink != null) {
      print('Handled dynamic link: $deepLink');
      navigateTo(deepLink);
    }
  }

  void navigateTo(Uri deepLink) {
    if (deepLink.path == '/profile') {
      var userID = deepLink.queryParameters['userID'];
      Navigator.of(context).pushNamed('/profile', arguments: userID);
    }
  }

  // Example: Creating a deep link and initiating a launch
  void launchDeepLink(String deepLink) async {
    if (await canLaunch(deepLink)) {
      await launch(deepLink);
    } else {
      throw 'Could not launch $deepLink';
    }
  }
}

// Sample Profile Widget

class Profile extends StatelessWidget {

  final String userID;

  Profile({required this.userID});

  @override
  Widget build(BuildContext context) {
    return Scaffold(
      appBar: AppBar(
        title: Text('User Profile'),
      ),
      body: Center(
        child: Text('Viewing Profile: $userID'),
      ),
    );
  }
}

// Home Page

class MyHomePage extends StatelessWidget {
  @override
  Widget build(BuildContext context) {
    return Scaffold(
      appBar: AppBar(
        title: Text('Deep Linking Demo'),
      ),
      body: Center(
        child: Column(
          mainAxisAlignment: MainAxisAlignment.center,
          children: <Widget>[
            ElevatedButton(
              onPressed: () {
                // Example: Generating a deep link and launching it
                var deepLink = MyApp().generateUserProfileLink('123');
                MyApp().launchDeepLink(deepLink);
              },
              child: Text('Open Profile with User ID 123'),
            ),
          ],
        ),
      ),
    );
  }
}

Local Storage in Flutter usually involves key-value stores, databases, or file
systems like preferences, shared preferences, or sqflite.


1. SHARED PREFERENCES

 * Overview: For small user-specific data, ideal for app settings.

 * Features: Persistence across app sessions, dynamic updates.

 * Code: Example using shared_preferences package:

   import 'package:shared_preferences/shared_preferences.dart';

   // Writing
   SharedPreferences prefs = await SharedPreferences.getInstance();
